text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild]]%0a%0a!Accent Discrimination in Technology%0a%0a:Author: david_h%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aAmazon Alexa and Google Home are unable to understand some accents more than others.%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aThe following article from the Washington Post shows that even technology can discriminate against specific accents: https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/2018/business/alexa-does-not-understand-your-accent/%0a%0aWhile the discrimination is not as intentional as other examples, the fact is that these technologies rely on datasets of people's accents. If the voice recognition service is trained on "standard accents" then it is implicitly discriminating against "non-standard accents". As such, accents of immigrants are the hardest for Google and Alexa to understand. The study found that Spanish and Chinese accents consistently scored the lowest in Alexa and Google understandability.%0a%0aThe article shows how a news headline is interpreted by Alexa differently depending on the accent of the speaker. With standard American English, it was able to detect "trump bulldozed fox news host showing again why he likes phone injuries" which is correct except for "injuries" (interviews). However, when a nonnative English speaker spoke, Alexa detected it as "from bulldozed of fox new house showing again why lights phone interview". This makes it almost impossible for nonnative English speakers, specifically those with Chinese or Spanish accents to use these voice assistants.%0a%0aThe solution is not easy. Since there are so many variations in nonnative English speech as compared to standard American English, engineers at Google and Amazon as well as linguists working with these technologies, it is harder to train the speakers to recognize these accents. A study found a correlation between diversity in voice data and being able to understand more accents. Since the dataset is not diverse enough when it comes to nonnative English accents, the speakers were not able to recognize them.%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210505-000555-838160#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Technology forcing adaptation of accents %0a-> - AlexanderW%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0ahttps://www.scientificamerican.com/article/speech-recognition-tech-is-yet-another-example-of-bias/%0a%0aA pertinent consequence of this accent discrimination is that technology is forcing people to change the way they speaking. Mainly, they are forced to Anglicize their name or other words, as well as even change or modulate their own accent to be more "American". But this seems to be against the ideals of technology, where technology conforms to the individual instead of the individual conforming to technology. This causes many people conflict between maintaining identity and being more 'understood', which further emphasizes the importance of diversifying the AI's training data, as David mentioned above.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210505-000555-838160#%0a#foxbegin 210506-111335-943340#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Difficulty using automated phone answering services %0a-> - xiranw%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aIn recent years, many businesses, instead of always having a human receptionist on the line, have switched to using automated phone answering systems to perform simple requests and/or route callers. While these systems reduce cost, they present usability challenges for callers with accents. My father, who has a Chinese accent, has complained to me a few times about how these systems are not able to interpret his responses correctly. The most memorable one was how the system asked him to say his phone number but could not interpret his pronunciation of eight. It also gave him no option to simply type his phone number, so it was a quite frustrating experience.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210506-111335-943340#%0a#foxbegin 210508-032058-954470#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Speech-to-text and AAVE %0a-> - lauray%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0ahttps://builtin.com/artificial-intelligence/racial-bias-speech-recognition-systems%0a%0aThis article also mentions how the error rate for Black speakers was 35%25 compared to the 19%25 for white speakers, highlighting how AAVE is underrepresented in many training sets, resulting in them being poorly understood and reproduced. The article talks about how voice recognition software is unable to catch the nuances of AAVE such as the use of “be” in “they be happy” vs “they are happy” as well as the tones that are used in AAVE. Additionally, with the language model, the software tries to correct things and fill in gaps which likely links to societal bias especially since Black names are more commonly put next to things with a bad connotation. Essentially, there needs to be more equal datasets and training done to allow the software to understand AAVE.%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210508-032058-954470#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: E:)%0a(:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild:)
