diff:1620444058:1620299615:=71,82d70%0a%3c #foxbegin 210508-032058-954470#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!Speech-to-text and AAVE %0a%3c -> - lauray%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c https://builtin.com/artificial-intelligence/racial-bias-speech-recognition-systems%0a%3c %0a%3c This article also mentions how the error rate for Black speakers was 35%25 compared to the 19%25 for white speakers, highlighting how AAVE is underrepresented in many training sets, resulting in them being poorly understood and reproduced. The article talks about how voice recognition software is unable to catch the nuances of AAVE such as the use of “be” in “they be happy” vs “they are happy” as well as the tones that are used in AAVE. Additionally, with the language model, the software tries to correct things and fill in gaps which likely links to societal bias especially since Black names are more commonly put next to things with a bad connotation. Essentially, there needs to be more equal datasets and training done to allow the software to understand AAVE.%0a%3c %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 210508-032058-954470#%0a
